# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1910-chalmers-award
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The **1901 Cleveland Blues season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] It was the franchise's first in the majors, being one of the original franchises of the American League.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Called the "Blues" or "Bluebirds", the team finished seventh out of eight teams.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Spiders were dissolved after winning only 20 games and losing 134 in the 1899 season along with the Louisville Colonels, Baltimore Orioles, and the Washington Senators, leaving the National League with eight teams to begin the 1900 season.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As a result, 1900 marked the first year since 1886 during which the city of Cleveland did not have a team affiliated with Major League Baseball.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] During this time, Cleveland had a minor league baseball team, known as the Bluebirds or Blues due to their all-blue uniforms, which finished their season with a 63–73 record and finished sixth.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The American League became a major league before the 1901 season.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the American League made the jump to major league status, many players jumped ship, including Cy Young and Nap Lajoie, which led the National League to call them an "outlaw league" in November 1900.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the 1901 season came underway in April, and as the war between the two leagues erupted, the Cleveland franchise, now known as the Blues, began its first official season as a Major League Baseball team.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Blues played their first game of the season against the Chicago White Stockings on April 24, 1901.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] This was the first games in the history of the American League; three other games scheduled that day were rained out.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The starting lineup consisted of: Ollie Pickering (RF), Jack McCarthy (LF), Frank Genins (CF), Candy LaChance (1B), Bill Bradley (3B), Erve Beck (2B), Bill Hallman (SS), Bob Wood (C), and Bill Hoffer (P).
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Hoffer allowed seven runs in the first two innings and the Blues failed to recover, as they lost the game 8–2, earning the first loss in American League history.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] In the second game of the season, Beck hit the first home run in American League history off pitcher John Skopec, but the Blues lost again, 7–3.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 9, 1901, Earl Moore threw the first no-hitter in the history of the franchise and the American League.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Blues lost to Chicago by a score of 4–2 despite allowing no hits.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 23, Cleveland scored nine runs with the bases empty and two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning to beat Washington 14–13.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The **1901 Milwaukee Brewers** were an American professional baseball team.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] This was the final season of the Milwaukee Brewers team that operated from 1894 to 1901, one of multiple teams in Milwaukee's professional baseball history to use the Brewers nickname, and the only season the team competed at the major-league level.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Brewers finished eighth in the inaugural season of the American League with a record of 48 wins and 89 losses, 35+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] After the season, the major-league franchise relocated and became the St.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] Louis Browns, where they remained through the 1953 season, after which the franchise again relocated and became the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] A franchise in the minor-league American Association played in Milwaukee from 1902 through 1952 using the Milwaukee Brewers name.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] 4/25/01: In the first game of the season in Detroit, the Brewers held a 13–4 lead going into the ninth inning.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Detroit Tigers scored 10 runs in the bottom of the inning to win, a record which still stands as the greatest ninth inning comeback in major league baseball history.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] The **1910 Chalmers Award** was one of the first attempts to honor Major League Baseball's top players.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Introduced by Hugh Chalmers, president of the Chalmers Motor Car Company, the award promised a luxurious Chalmers Model 30 to the player with the highest batting average for the 1910 season.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] The initiative symbolized the emerging relationship between sports and commercial endorsements.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] The award became the center of a major controversy involving Ty Cobb of the Detroit Tigers and Napoleon Lajoie of the Cleveland Naps, both future Hall of Famers.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] The competition for the title was intense, culminating in a controversial final day of the season in which tactics employed by the St.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Louis Browns, playing against Lajoie, were questioned for their fairness.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Chalmers awarded an automobile to both Cobb and Lajoie.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] The 1910 Chalmers Award is notable not only for the controversy it engendered but also for its role in shaping future accolades in baseball.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] It set a precedent for recognizing player excellence, leading to the development of the Most Valuable Player Award in subsequent decades.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] The Chalmers Award was presented annually until 1914, when it was discontinued.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Before the 1910 Major League Baseball season, Hugh Chalmers of the Chalmers Automobile Company announced a promotion in which a Chalmers Model 30 automobile would be awarded to the batting champions for Major League Baseball's American and National Leagues.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] At the start of the final day of the season, Ty Cobb of the Detroit Tigers held a slim lead in the race for the American League batting title, just a few percentage points ahead of the Cleveland Naps' Nap Lajoie.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Cobb was generally disliked by opponents but Lajoie was popular.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Cobb did not play in the Tigers' final two games of the season and finished with a batting average of .385.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Lajoie played in a doubleheader on the last day of the season against the St.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Jack O'Connor, the Browns' manager, allegedly ordered rookie third baseman Red Corriden to play on the outfield grass.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] This all but conceded a base hit for any ball that Lajoie bunted.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Lajoie finished with eight hits in eight at-bats, resulting in a season batting average of .384 (227 hits in 591 at-bats).
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] His final at-bat resulted in a wild throw to first base, which was scored as an error.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Under baseball rules, when a player reaches base on a fielding error, it is treated as a hitless at-bat, thus lowering the hitter's batting average.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] After news broke of the scandal, a writer for the *St.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Louis is up in arms over the deplorable spectacle, conceived in stupidity and executed in jealousy." The issue was brought to American League president Ban Johnson, who declared all batting averages official and Cobb the champion (.385069 to .384095).
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] However, Chalmers awarded automobiles to both Cobb and Lajoie, essentially declaring a tie.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] O'Connor and coach Harry Howell, who tried to bribe the official scorer to change the error to a hit, were banned from baseball for their roles in the affair.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] For the following season, Chalmers gave its award to the league's most valuable player instead of the player with the highest batting average.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Cobb won the Chalmers Award in 1911 in his best year, hitting .420.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Chalmers continued the award through the 1914 season, after which it was discontinued.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Chalmers ceased operations in 1923, although it was a predecessor to the modern company Chrysler.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Cobb and Lajoie were eventually elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] In 1978, sports statistician Pete Palmer discovered a 1910 discrepancy in Cobb's career hit total, and the story was broken by *The Sporting News* in April 1981.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] Cobb is credited with 4,191-lifetime hits (still the total on MLB.com), but a 1910 Detroit Tigers box score was counted twice in the season-ending calculations.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] The mistake caused the statisticians to award Cobb an extra 2-for-3, which credited him with two non-existent hits and erroneously raised his 1910 batting average from .383 to .385.
[src:1910-chalmers-award/1910-chalmers-award] As Lajoie had a .384 average for the season, the revised figure would have cost Cobb one of his 12 batting titles, reduced his career average to .366 and given the 1910 batting championship to Lajoie.
